## The Video File

**HoldtLoop.mp4** — lives at `/root/HoldtLoop.mp4` on the VPS.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Resolution | 1920×1080 |
| Framerate | 6fps |
| Codec | H.264 video + AAC audio |
| Duration | ~1h40m (6000 seconds) |
| Size | ~1.28GB |
| Content | 480-frame pixel art animation looped over a lo-fi music track |

When FFmpeg reaches the end of the file, `-stream_loop -1` restarts it seamlessly.

### How It Was Built (locally, not on VPS)

**Step 1 — PNGs to silent video:**
```bash
ffmpeg -framerate 6 -i "%d.png" -c:v libx264 -pix_fmt yuv420p holdt_6fps.mp4
```
480 PNG frames → 80-second silent video at 6fps.

**Step 2 — Loop animation + add music:**
```bash
ffmpeg -stream_loop -1 -i holdt_6fps.mp4 -i LofiLoop.wav -map 0:v -map 1:a -c:v libx264 -g 12 -keyint_min 12 -c:a aac -t 6000 HoldtLoop.mp4
```
Loops the 80s animation ~75 times to fill the 1h40m music track. `-g 12 -keyint_min 12` sets 2-second keyframe intervals (YouTube requires ≤4s for "Good" stream health).

**Step 3 — Upload to VPS:**
```bash
scp HoldtLoop.mp4 root@138.197.9.139:/root/
```

---

## The RTMP Destination

FFmpeg pushes to Restream's ingest URL. Restream forwards to YouTube (and optionally Twitch).

```
rtmp://live.restream.io/live/re_10860387_75ea120b5509c4a2572f
```

This is the Restream stream key. Both OBS and the VPS push to the same ingest point — Restream doesn't care which encoder is sending.

---

## Daily Operations

### Start the radio

```bash
ssh root@138.197.9.139
tmux attach -t stream
```

If the tmux session is gone:
```bash
tmux new -s stream
```

Then run:
```bash
ffmpeg -re -stream_loop -1 -i HoldtLoop.mp4 -c:v copy -c:a copy -f flv rtmp://live.restream.io/live/re_10860387_75ea120b5509c4a2572f
```

Wait for `time=` values to start scrolling. That confirms the stream is running. **Close the terminal window immediately.** Do not press any keys — accidental Ctrl+Z suspends FFmpeg.

### Stop the radio

```bash
ssh root@138.197.9.139
tmux attach -t stream
```

Press **Q**. FFmpeg exits. Done.

### Check if it's running

```bash
ssh root@138.197.9.139
tmux attach -t stream
```

If `time=` values are scrolling → it's running. Close the window.

---

## The Handoff (VPS ↔ OBS)

YouTube/Restream accept one encoder at a time. When you go live from OBS, the VPS must stop first. When you sign off, restart it.

### Going live from OBS

1. SSH in → `tmux attach -t stream` → press **Q** (kills VPS stream)
2. Close terminal
3. Start streaming in OBS (OBS pushes to same Restream ingest)
4. You're live

### Returning to radio after stream

1. Stop streaming in OBS
2. SSH in → `tmux attach -t stream` (or `tmux new -s stream`)
3. Run the FFmpeg command (see above)
4. Wait for `time=` → close terminal
5. Holdt's back

**The gap:** There's ~30–60 seconds of dead air during each switch. YouTube viewers see nothing briefly. Accepted for now.

---

## Gotchas (Learned the Hard Way)

### 1. Restream YouTube toggle defaults to OFF after reconnects

After ANY channel reconnect in Restream (OAuth re-auth, stream key reset, removing/re-adding channel), the YouTube toggle in Restream → Channels defaults to **OFF**. Restream shows "Sending data..." but YouTube shows nothing.

**Fix:** Go to Restream → Channels → click the toggle next to your YouTube channel to turn it ON.

**Always check this after starting the radio.**

### 2. YouTube Studio shows "No data" — that's normal

YouTube Studio defaults to the "Default stream" dashboard, which always shows "No data" / "Connect your encoder." Restream creates its own stream entry via OAuth — it doesn't use the default key.

**Fix:** In YouTube Studio → Go Live → click the dropdown at the top that says "Stream key: Default stream" → switch to the Restream-created stream. That's where your live data is.

### 3. Never touch stream settings in YouTube Studio

Restream owns the YouTube connection via OAuth. If you reset the stream key in YouTube Studio, it breaks Restream's connection. You'll have to remove and re-add the YouTube channel in Restream entirely.

**Rule:** YouTube Studio is for monitoring only. Restream manages the connection.

### 4. Don't press keys while FFmpeg is running

Once `time=` is scrolling, close the terminal. Arrow keys and accidental Ctrl+Z will suspend or crash FFmpeg. tmux keeps the session alive regardless of whether your terminal is open.

### 5. Keyframe interval matters

The initial HoldtLoop.mp4 build omitted `-g 12 -keyint_min 12`, which produced ~41-second keyframe intervals. YouTube reported "Poor" stream health. The corrected build command (in the "How It Was Built" section above) includes these flags. At 6fps, `-g 12` = keyframe every 2 seconds, which YouTube considers "Good."

### 6. `-re` flag is required for file-to-RTMP

Without `-re`, FFmpeg reads the file as fast as disk allows and floods the RTMP server. `-re` throttles playback to 1× real-time. It's an input flag — must go before `-i`.

### 7. FFmpeg will eventually die on its own

Restream drops connections occasionally (maintenance, network issues). When it does, FFmpeg exits and the stream goes dark until you manually SSH in and restart. A systemd service or shell wrapper with auto-restart is the fix (not yet implemented as of March 2026).

### 8. YouTube does NOT kill streams at 12 hours

YouTube stops **archiving** (VOD) after 12 hours, but the live stream continues indefinitely. If you need the VOD, record locally. The stream itself won't be terminated.

